Force libgit2 to re-read the index every request.

A long-running gitstatusd caches a libgit2 `git_index*` between requests and
refreshes it with `git_index_read_ex(force=0)`. When another process (`git
commit`, `git add`, rebase, …) rewrites `.git/index`, libgit2's stat-based
change detection does not reliably notice — `was_new_index` stays false, the
cached entries keep their pre-mutation mtime/size, and the daemon reports
phantom staged/unstaged counts until the daemon dies. Reproduces deterministi-
cally; debug log shows "Index and HEAD unchanged; staged = 1" followed by
"Dirty candidate (modified): a.txt: fsize 3 => 7".

Symptom cluster covers powerlevel10k#2473, gitstatus#474, #452, #197, #2232,
#2387 — each previously diagnosed as a different config trigger (`feature.
manyFiles`, `index.skipHash`, `core.untrackedCache`, fsmonitor). The real
mechanism is libgit2's change-detection: with `force=1` we bypass it and pay
~5 ms per request on a 7 k-file repo to always re-parse the index.

Upstream is on life support (powerlevel10k#2681) so this is carried locally.

diff --git a/src/repo.cc b/src/repo.cc
--- a/src/repo.cc
+++ b/src/repo.cc
@@ -146,7 +146,7 @@ IndexStats Repo::GetIndexStats(const git_oid* head, git_config* cfg) {

   if (git_index_) {
     int new_index;
-    VERIFY(!git_index_read_ex(git_index_, 0, &new_index)) << GitError();
+    VERIFY(!git_index_read_ex(git_index_, 1, &new_index)) << GitError();
     if (new_index) {
       head_ = {};
       index_.reset();
